Restoring the very American ideal that labor rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a law to protect union organization as a civil right.
“The way unions work, middle-class jobs work,” says Ellison, a Democratic senator for Minnesota who co-chairs the Congressional Committee.
That is why I am so proud to be able to introduce, together with the model of the occasional rights of John Lewis, a law strengthening the position of employees.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to defend against discrimination in union organizing as in other forms of discrimination – and stop anti-union forces
Adjusting the Labour Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination to join unions, go to civil court - and award compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents of the law are proposing is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states — Americans once encouraged countries around the world to adopt, expand, and respect labor rights.
There were times, and millions of Americans still remember them, when the country in one breath promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assembly.
When the United States seized Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toja's military autocracy was replaced by democracy.
They were convinced that employees and their unions played a role in the formation of the new Japan, they included language in them and openly recognized that “the right of employees to assemble, collectively negotiate and act is guaranteed.”
When the United States seized Germany after World War II, General Dwight D. Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans realized that workers would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, and therefore included a clause that openly states: “The right to form associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or profession.
The provisions that will restrict this right or seek to harm it will be repealed. The measures leading to the fulfillment of such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global treaty, the drafters and Roosevelt’s guarantees that “everyone has the right to form and join trade unions to protect their interests.”
Americans have accepted for generations the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to form labor unions – and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies in a position of equal partner – must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today everyone knows that the trade unions have not diminished the strength of the nation, but have expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to unprecedented levels.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is greatly delayed.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are restoring the ideals that have elevated America and made it a true promise of democracy.
A judge has temporarily blocked a law that could have shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that lawyers said would likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
The decree, signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June and due to enter into force on September 1, would require abortion practitioners to have the right to admit a patient to a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge’s ruling means that doctors can temporarily continue to perform legal abortions and must obtain this permission in the meantime.
“The proposing party will be able to legally conduct its business and, in the meantime, obtain a permit,” federal judge John deGravelles said in a statement.
The hearing will be scheduled within one month so that the judge can issue a more permanent resolution regarding the law.
Abortion rights activists welcomed the resolution, which is the latest in a series of similar measures, and said it would give doctors more time to get permission.
“Today’s decision ensures that women in Louisiana will be safe from the insidious law that is designed to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and CEO of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which sued to block the law on behalf of three of the five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applied to doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs and were also seeking permission to do so.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such provisions unconstitutional.
A key piece of Texas law that would close most of the remaining clinics in the state was blocked by federal judges on Friday.
Advocates for women’s abortion rights, along with the Association of American Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, argue that the need for such a permit imposes requirements on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argued that the measures were intended to protect women’s health, and some also welcomed the fact that clinics would be closed due to the measures.
According to the Center for Reproductive Rights, there is only one abortion practitioner in Louisiana.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure for fear of his safety, the group said.
In response, Louisiana authorities said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while waiting for the grant application to be processed.
