Why the Universe Can Have More Dimensions and We Can't See Them
Physicists usually don't write best-sellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University did in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe became the most accessible way for the layman to penetrate the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists today deal with - an effort to unify two brilliantly working but mutually incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that finding a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the fundamental problem between two key theories (for at the moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to the layman.
In addition, Greene had handled the complex material so freshly and engagingly that he could not be blamed for not including so much of it in his book.
In addition, he largely corrected his "mistake" in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and Hidden Reality.
The author probably wouldn’t mind if his book aged faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with the ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a little more lively in this area (for example, because the LHC accelerator will finally go on "full gas"), so it is a good time to enter the Greene non-violently open door of the world of modern physics.
How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound silly, fantastic, strange, or mystical.
However, it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us turn our eyes for a moment from the universe as a whole to something more mundane, namely a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine stretching a hundred-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the whole scene from a half-kilometer distance (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you will easily notice a long hose stretched in a horizontal direction, but if you do not suffer from sharp vision, you will hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on the hose has only one dimension in which it can walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
If someone asks you where the ant was at that moment, you will answer with only one information: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from a distance of half a kilometer, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose is thick.
If we magnify everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping a hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is obvious that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/against the direction of movement of the clockwise hands", i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant, you need to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where there is a coiling hose on the circle.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (Note: Experts note that this chapter focuses purely on the failure theory of strings.
Non-disruptive aspects are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.)
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circumference, marked by a circular arrow, is short and curved.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The size along the hose is long and easy to see.
The size of the enveloping circumference of the hose is short, "curved" and less noticeable.
In order to realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
The above example illustrates an important feature of spatial dimensions.
The fact that they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, large, and therefore directly visible, or on the contrary small, curled and much less visible.
Of course, in the above case, we did not exactly overdo it in order to reveal the "curved" dimension wrapping the thickness of the hose.
I had to get a telescope to help me.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - we would only reveal the coiled dimension with great effort.
In 1919, Kaluza sent Einstein an article in which he argued with the astounding idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions that we all know.
Kaluza justified his radical claim by saying that the extra dimension provides an elegant and convincing framework in which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises as to how this observation of Kaluza goes together with the obvious fact that we see exactly three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly expressed and clarified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the claim that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and curved dimensions.
This means that, like the dimensions in the direction of the length of the hose, our universe has three large, large and easily visible dimensions, the existence of which we are aware at every moment.
But by analogy with the circular circumference of the garden hose, the universe can have additional dimensions, tightly rolled into a space so small that they have remained hidden from our most advanced experimental apparatus.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluza's remarkable design, let's stay with the hose for a while.
Imagine that we draw a fairly dense series of circles on the circumference of the hose.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With the telescope, thanks to the drawing, we will now reveal the curved dimension even easier, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but apart from one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, four-dimensional together.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imagination a little, let us note the illustration in Fig. 3; it shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of space in the same way as we enlarge the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of the space from the previous level.
Our universe can have extra dimensions (we see them at the fourth level of magnification) if they are folded into a sufficiently small space; this explains that we have not yet directly observed them.
The square grid represents the commonly known "large" dimensions, while the circle is a new, tiny and curved dimension.
Just like loops of threads in a densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of the usual dimensions - we just drew them only to the intersections in a square network for the sake of clarity.
The background of Figure 4 shows the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - at such common scales as meters, represented by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each of the following pictures, we focus on the small area of the previous picture; we enlarge it to make it visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see in the first few levels of magnification.
But as we move on to the microscopic properties of the geometry of space - the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, circular, coiled dimension, similar to strings in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every location in the direction of large dimensions, much like a hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn a circular dimension only in some regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluza and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of the geometry of space.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also note important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has only one large dimension.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly curved dimension is extremely miniature, it is much more difficult to recognize it - as well as the circular circumference of the hose - than to observe obvious, large and extensive dimensions.
If the size of the extra dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it beyond the power of our state-of-the-art magnification tools.
But the most important thing is that the extra dimension is not just a round bump inside normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration erroneously suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of three common large dimensions.
It is a dimension independent of the other three dimensions, just as the dimensions of the top-down, left-right, and front-rear are independent of (and perpendicular to) each other.
A sufficiently small ant would be able to move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the three usual still position in the circular dimension; if we count the time, then the data five, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
