Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed.
A woman in Britain describes how she thought she would die after being misdiagnosed for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking she had only a few years left to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said that poor diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
It is estimated that approximately 23,000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which can manifest as motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, clumsy walking and twisted toes.
Insensitivity or pain may also occur in the affected, this condition is incurable and progressive, which means that over time the symptoms worsen.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich's ataxia (FA), a disease with a very poor prognosis.
She believed that by the time she celebrated her eighteenth birthday, she would be strapped to a wheelchair and dead by the time she was thirty.
A mother of two, now 51, says: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same things as everyone else.
Every day I fell and it took me longer.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboards with the other kids, and I was bullied at school because of the way I walked and ran.”
When Rodgers was thirteen and had several surgeries to loosen her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of her doctor’s departure from the room and looked into her documentation, where she learned she was suffering from FA.
“I felt guilty because I was spying, so I didn’t tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked for information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Association,” she says.
When they answered, I was in shock, completely panicked.
I thought that by the time I was eighteen I would be in a wheelchair, and by the time I was twenty-five I would be dead, and in the meantime I would gradually lose all my faculties.
I was all alone and planning a funeral.”
When she was seventeen, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she had expected, and she asked her surgeon.
He just stood up and hugged her and said, “Honey, I don’t think you have the disease, or you’d be in a wheelchair by now.
I think it will be something much less life-threatening.”
After passing several genetic tests, he was found to have CMT.
"When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a lucky kid," she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched a month of CMT awareness to raise awareness of the disease.
Entrepreneurs in the Washington area: with the turn of the economy, taxes rise
A growing economy means more customers, higher sales and new jobs.
And higher taxes.
According to a new survey released last week, state and local taxes on firms in the country have risen slightly over the past year, with firms in Washington no exception.
Entrepreneurs in Maryland and Virginia combined contributed $27.6 billion to state and local coffers in fiscal 2013, a 3.8 percent increase over the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
Tax burdens – state and local – rose 4.3% to $671 billion last year, up from 3.9% last year, the third consecutive year of growth after 2009 and 2010, when taxes were cut.
According to a study conducted by professional firm Ernst & Young and political group Center on State Taxation, state taxes increased faster, by 4.3%, than local taxes, by 3.9%.
More than half of the county's tax revenue, 56%, is from trade taxes, and 36% of Maryland's income is from companies.
Virginia, with 28 percent, has the least tax revenue from business.
The researchers say that the majority share of tax revenue growth comes from an increase in the value of real estate belonging to firms, which this year for three consecutive years with growth of -1% increased by 3.7%.
Although most of the profits come from big states like California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same situation is in Washington.
Companies in D.C., Maryland, and Virginia paid more than $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up 4.2% year-on-year from $9.6 billion in 2012.
The apparent increase in the value of real estate, however, is not so much driving up state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property tax accounts for less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For businesses in Virginia and D.C., real estate tax accounts for nearly half of state and local taxes.
“Maryland owns a lot of real estate companies, especially the tax base around D.C., the government, or non-profit organizations that don’t pay taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
So Maryland is forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent increase in business tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovering real estate market.
According to the data, business income also seems to be increasing.
Companies in the region have published a corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, up from $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland's corporate income taxes raised $1 billion, the most in the region.
Although they are heading in the same direction, the local tax burden on entrepreneurs is not growing as fast in these three places.
The growth rate in D.C. was at the national average level, at 4.3%, while Maryland's growth was significantly higher, at 4.9%.
In Virginia alone, the tax increase was below the average, at 4.1%.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax rate of all three counties (all with the same tax rate), at 6%.
The corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25%, while the D.C. average remains relatively high, at 9.975%.
A similar study conducted by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce this year found that Virginia has lower state and local taxes and a generally more favorable tax climate than Maryland.
The D.C. study didn't evaluate.
Despite this advantage, Virginia faces pressure from competition from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a law lowering the corporate tax rate from 6.9% to 6%, just like Virginia, and next year the tax will be reduced to 5%.
If the state continues to meet its income targets in the coming year, the statutory income tax rate could be reduced to 3% in 2017.
According to a recent study, small businesses in Washington are doing better and therefore pay higher state and local taxes.
Trade tax paid by small businesses as a personal income tax — the structure of compensating for cost increases by raising prices under which most businesses are organized — in D.C., Maryland, and Virginia rose 20% last year to $2.4 billion, much faster than other taxes.
The researchers say the trend and nationwide trade tax increases are likely to continue next year, with total tax revenues from sales to state and local governments rising to 6.2 percent compared to the same period last year in the first three quarters of 2014.
Washington, however, may lag behind others because cutting government spending takes its toll on the labor market.
